"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151872","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-28","<p>In common with other rail franchises, the West Midlands Trains Franchise Agreement includes a standard provision whereby the Secretary of State is able to, at his discretion, reimburse net losses arising from Industrial Action. This can be viewed at Clause 5 of Schedule 8.1 of Franchise Agreement which is on the Department’s web site at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/837515/west-midlands-2017-franchise-agreement.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/837515/west-midlands-2017-franchise-agreement.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-10-28T14:58:03.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151872/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151872/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151872/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-23","West Midlands Trains: Strikes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 15 May 2003 to Question 113237 on rail strikes, whether West Midlands Trains has an indemnification clause in its franchise agreement with the Department for Transport allowing it to apply for reimbursement for revenues lost as a consequence of official industrial action.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","4373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151873","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-28","<p>There has been no correspondence between the Department and West Midlands Trains on this subject.</p><p> </p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-10-28T14:53:25.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151873/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151873/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151873/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-23","West Midlands Trains: Strikes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 15 May 2003 to Question 113237 on rail strikes, whether (a) he or (b) his Department has had any correspondence with West Midlands Trains on reimbursement for potential industrial action.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","4374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151874","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-29","<p>The Minister of Foreign Affairs of Bahrain and I discussed a wide range of areas of bilateral co-operation, including recent political and security developments in the Middle East, economic growth, security, human rights, healthcare, education, and trade.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-10-29T13:09:13.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151874/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151874/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151874/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-23","Bahrain: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what matters the Minister of State for the Middle East and North Africa and the Bahraini Minister of Foreign Affairs discussed at the UK-Bahrain Joint Working Group on 17 October 2019.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","4375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151875","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-31","<p>The UK and Bahrain continue to have a close and important relationship, which has flourished for more than 200 years. We cooperate on a number of pillars: defence; security; trade and investment. We work together on shared concerns about regional issues and the UK continues to provide technical assistance to Bahrain’s ongoing reform agenda.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-10-31T17:05:06.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151875/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151875/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151875/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-23","Bahrain: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of diplomatic relations between UK and Bahrain.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","4376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151876","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-31","<p>We regularly discuss human rights and reform with the Government of Bahrain, including at the biannual UK-Bahrain Joint Working Group. We welcome the progress made by Bahrain on their reform programme, including the introduction of the new legislation on alternatives to punishment and new proposed legislation on juvenile justice. Bahrain remains a Foreign and Commonwealth Office human rights priority country and the British Government continues to encourage the Government of Bahrain to meet its human rights obligations, in both public and private conversations.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-10-31T17:06:48.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151876/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151876/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151876/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-23","Bahrain: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what (a) human rights issues and (b) human rights abuse cases the Minister of State for the Middle East and North Africa raised with his Bahraini counterpart at the UK-Bahrain Joint Working Group on 17 October 2019.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","4377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151877","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-11-04","<p>The government does not favour the introduction of caps on private rents as this could restrict investment in the private rented sector. From 1915 to the late 1980s, successive governments implemented policies to control or restrict private rents, which coincided with the decline in the private rented sector from nine-tenths of the housing stock in 1915 to one tenth in 1991. <br> <br> Rent caps have lead to worse property conditions for tenants by discouraging investment in existing accommodation.</p>","Tatton","Esther McVey",,"2019-11-04T15:41:56.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151877/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151877/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151877/answer","Tatton","Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151877/answer/previousversion/2256","Biography information for Esther McVey","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-10-23","Affordable Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of introducing rent freezes to maintain affordable housing for low-income households.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","4287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151878","Home Office","false","2019-10-28","<p>Border Force search lorries, trailers and containers entering the UK on a targeted or intelligence-led basis. Border Force have also invested tens of millions of pounds in new infrastructure to enhance border security, with all freight vehicles entering the UK screened using a range of techniques. These include the use of carbon dioxide detectors, motion sensors and sniffer dogs to detect clandestine on-board lorries.</p><p>Border Force work closely with the Road Hauliers Association to prevent opportunist attacks on individual lorries, which can be frustrated by operators taking relatively simple measures to secure their vehicles.</p><p>Hauliers travelling to the UK are expected to operate effective security measures to prevent illegal migrants entering their vehicles. Border Force fine drivers and operators who have failed to implement such measures and migrants have been discovered in their vehicles.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-10-28T17:39:58.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151878/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151878/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151878/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-23","Smuggling: Bulgaria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether enhanced security checks are applied to vehicles entering the UK from Bulgaria for the detection of illegal immigrants and contraband.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","4251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151879","Cabinet Office","false","2019-10-28","<p>The Government is making all necessary preparations to ensure that we are ready for leaving the EU whatever the circumstances. We want to ensure the country is prepared at every level.</p><p>HM Treasury routinely monitors economic conditions and risks, and the Government has a range of mechanisms available to support vulnerable people. We stand ready to take appropriate action if economic conditions change. Furthermore, officials make estimates of the direct impact of spending decisions on household living standards, and would continue to do so in responding to challenges arising from leaving the EU without a deal.</p><p>We are committed to a strong safety-net for those who need it. This includes a well-established system of hardship payments, benefit advances and budgeting loans as an additional safeguard for those who need them. Additionally, the government has been working with local authorities to understand how a no-deal exit might impact upon their services, including services for vulnerable people.</p><p> </p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith","3773 ; 4343","2019-10-28T17:50:56.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151879/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151879/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151879/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-10-23","Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish the (a) information he holds on the effect on disadvantaged communities of the UK leaving the EU without a deal and (b) plans he has in place to mitigate that effect.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","4261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151880","Treasury","false","2019-10-28","<p>The Treasury sets the Northern Ireland administration’s overall Financial Transaction Capital budget through the normal operation of the Barnett formula.</p><p> </p><p>The annual Financial Transaction Capital budgets of the Northern Ireland administration and total Financial Transaction Capital returned to HM Treasury by the Northern Ireland administration for the period 2012-13 to 2020-21 is set out in the table:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>(£m)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Financial Transaction Capital budgets</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Financial Transaction Capital returned to HMT</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>11.8</p></td><td><p>0.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>46.8</p></td><td><p>0.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>62.8</p></td><td><p>0.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>129.0</p></td><td><p>0.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>59.2</p></td><td><p>34.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>166.9</p></td><td><p>109.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018-19</p></td><td><p>182.2</p></td><td><p>171.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2019-20</p></td><td><p>192.4</p></td><td><p>n/a*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2020-21</p></td><td><p>192.8</p></td><td><p>n/a*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1043.9</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>315.8</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*Underspend data is not available until the end of each financial year.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Financial transaction funding is ring-fenced for loans or equity investments to the private sector.</p><p> </p><p>The use of these Financial Transaction Capital budgets is a matter for the Northern Ireland administration. This includes the allocation of Financial Transaction Capital budgets to Northern Ireland departments, the drawdown of these allocations, approvals processes, and details of projects that have been funded.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak","4379 ; 4380 ; 4381 ; 4382","2019-10-28T16:30:01.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151880/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151880/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151880/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-23","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much Financial Transactions Capital funding Northern Ireland Government Departments have (a) requested and (b) received since the inception of that scheme in 2012-13.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","4378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151881","Department for International Trade","false","2019-10-28","<p>Over the past year, UK Export Finance (UKEF) has had frequent and ongoing engagement with multiple stakeholders on renewable energy in Argentina. Most recently, in September 2019, a UKEF official participated in a panel on renewable energy organised by the British Argentine Chamber of Commerce at the EIC Connect Energy event in Manchester.</p><p> </p><p>UKEF officials last visited Argentina in February 2018 where they met representatives from the renewable energy sector.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2019-10-28T11:01:37.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151881/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151881/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151881/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-10-23","Renewable Energy: Argentina","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, on what date representatives of UK Export Finance last met renewable energy developers in Argentina.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","4243"
