"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151989","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>Once the identities of the victims of the tragic incident in Grays are confirmed we will liaise with the relevant embassies on how to provide support to the victims’ families.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-11-05T14:34:51.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151989/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151989/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151989/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-23","Human Trafficking: Essex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department will provide financial assistance for repatriation of the bodies of the people discovered in a shipping container in Essex on 23 October 2019 once their identities are confirmed.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","4289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151990","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-10-30","<p>Perfume and fragrance manufacturers are required under Regulation (EC) No 1223/2009 on cosmetic products (“the Cosmetic Products Regulation”) to ensure that their products, including any chemical ingredients, are safe for human health. All cosmetic products must undergo a safety assessment. Annex III of the Cosmetic Products Regulation requires that the use of certain substances is subject to restriction. The presence of a substance listed in Annex III must be indicated in a product’s list of ingredients, in addition to the words parfum or aroma. At the moment, 26 fragrance allergens are listed in in this Annex, and the list of allergenic fragrances is kept under review. A Cosmetic Product Safety Report must be compiled before the product is placed on the market. This report may be inspected at any time by the enforcement authority.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Duncan of Springbank",,"2019-10-30T17:23:35.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151990/answer","Biography information for Lord Duncan of Springbank","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151990/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151990/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-10-23","Perfume: Chemicals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the chemicals contained in perfume and fragrance products, and any potential risks to human health.","false","Biography information for Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle",,"Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle","HL334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151991","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-10-30","<p>Under Regulation (EC) No 1223/2009 on cosmetic products (“the Cosmetics Regulation”) containers or packaging of cosmetic products (or on an enclosed or attached documentation) must set out a list of ingredients, including perfume and aromatic compositions and their raw materials. These perfume and aromatic compositions must be referred to as ‘parfum’ or ‘aroma’. Annex III of the Cosmetic Products Regulation requires that the use of certain substances is subject to restriction. The presence of a substance listed in Annex III must be indicated in a product’s list of ingredients, in addition to the words parfum or aroma. At the moment, 26 fragrance allergens are listed in in this Annex. The labelling must be on the carton, or if there is no outer packaging, then on the container. If the perfume or fragrance is small and difficult to label, the ingredient list may be on a leaflet provided with the product, or displayed close to where the product is offered for sale.</p>",,"Lord Duncan of Springbank",,"2019-10-30T17:23:17.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151991/answer","Biography information for Lord Duncan of Springbank","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151991/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151991/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-10-23","Perfume: Labelling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what requirements are placed on producers of perfume and fragrance products to list their ingredients on product packaging.","false","Biography information for Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle",,"Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle","HL335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151992","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-11-05","<p>Producers of domestic cleaning products are required to make consumers aware of the ingredients of their products through the EU Classification, Labelling and Packaging (CLP) Regulation (Regulation (EC) No. 1272/2008). Under this Regulation, suppliers of products containing hazardous chemical substances and mixtures are required to provide information on the label to identify any hazardous chemicals, explain what the hazards are and how to avoid them.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, under the EU Detergents Regulation (Regulation (EC) No. 648/2004), producers of detergents and cleaning products sold to the general public must also list the product ingredients on labels on product packaging and in ingredient data sheets. Enzymes, disinfectants, optical brighteners, perfumes and preservation agents must be listed on the label irrespective of their concentration. This information must appear in legible, visible and indelible characters on the packaging of detergents and cleaning products which are intended for the consumer.</p><p> </p><p>Producers must also prepare a full ingredient data sheet to be made available to medical personnel on request. A less detailed version of the ingredient data sheet must also be placed in the public domain via a website address on the product packaging.</p><p> </p><p>This information on ingredients enables consumers to make better informed choices about products.</p><p> </p><p>The levels of protection for people and the environment, including labelling requirements for ingredients and ingredient data sheets, will remain at least as high as at present when the UK leaves the EU.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2019-11-05T17:19:28.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151992/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151992/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151992/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-23","Detergents: Labelling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what requirements are placed on producers of domestic cleaning products to list their ingredients on product packaging.","false","Biography information for Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle",,"Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle","HL336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151993","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-10-30","<p>Perfume and fragrance manufacturers are required under Regulation (EC) No 1223/2009 on cosmetic products to ensure that their products are safe for human health. All cosmetics products must undergo a safety assessment. A Cosmetic Product Safety Report must be compiled before the product is placed on the market which may be inspected at any time by the enforcement authority.</p>",,"Lord Duncan of Springbank",,"2019-10-30T17:23:50.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151993/answer","Biography information for Lord Duncan of Springbank","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151993/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151993/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-10-23","Perfume: Safety","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what requirements are placed on perfume and fragrance manufacturers (1) to test, and (2) to demonstrate, the safety of their products for human health.","false","Biography information for Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle",,"Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle","HL337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151994","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-10-30","<p>The Government is committed to maintaining the same high standards of product safety and labelling for perfume and fragrance products when the UK leaves the EU.</p>",,"Lord Duncan of Springbank",,"2019-10-30T17:24:03.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151994/answer","Biography information for Lord Duncan of Springbank","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151994/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151994/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-10-23","Perfume: Safety","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have, if any, to change product safety and labelling requirements relating to perfume and fragrance products if the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle",,"Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle","HL338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151995","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-11-05","<p>The Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES) is implemented in the EU through a number of regulations known collectively as the EU Wildlife Trade Regulations (WTR), which put in place a system of permits and certificates for cross-border movement of specimens of endangered species. Under the EU (Withdrawal) Act, the WTR will become retained EU law on exit day. We have made EU Exit regulations to make this retained EU law work in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>With regard to a withdrawal agreement, current CITES controls and procedures in place between the UK and EU27 will continue during the implementation period. After EU Exit we will consider on an ongoing basis amendments necessary to continue to meet our obligations under CITIES in a UK context.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is a Party to CITIES in its own right, and will remain a Party after EU Exit. The UK will continue to meet the obligations and commitments under CITIES to work toward ensuring that no species becomes extinct as a result of unsustainable trade.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2019-11-05T17:34:51.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151995/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151995/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151995/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-23","Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the UK will maintain the current EU Wildlife Trade Regulations and therefore remain within the EU’s regulatory Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora framework, following a Brexit withdrawal agreement.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151996","Treasury","false","2019-11-01","<p>If the UK leaves the EU with an agreement then there will be no changes to social security coordination during the implementation period ending on 31 December 2020.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is working to protect UK workers in a no deal scenario by seeking an EU-wide approach or reciprocal bilateral arrangements with Member States to transitionally continue the current social security coordination rules in full until the end of December 2020. Where arrangements are put in place, individuals, employers and freelancers will continue to pay social security contributions in one country at a time.</p>",,"The Earl of Courtown",,"2019-11-01T09:28:35.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151996/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151996/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151996/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-23","Social Security: Self-employed","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to ensure that HM Revenue and Customs provides rebates for freelance workers in the EU27 who may incur double deductions of social security as a result of the invalidity of A1 certificates in the event of a no-deal Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151997","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-31","<p>​I am saddened that a minority of protesters have resorted to violence in Catalonia. It is important that all parties work to resolve their political differences peacefully and in line with the Spanish legal framework and constitution. The Government has been clear that the situation in the Autonomous Community of Catalonia is a matter for Spain, and that questions related to the issue of independence should be resolved within the proper constitutional and legal channels. The Minister for Europe and the Americas recently outlined this position to the Spanish Ambassador, and in Parliament on 15 October.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-10-31T15:26:46.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151997/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151997/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151997/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-23","Catalonia: Sovereignty","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Spain about that government's treatment of protesters in Catalonia and Barcelona.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151998","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-30","<p>​We remain fully committed to the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPoA), a key achievement of the global nuclear non-proliferation architecture, which is in our shared security interests. Since July, Iran has exceeded key JCPoA limits on uranium enrichment, uranium stockpiles and on 7 September announced suspension of the JCPoA's nuclear research and development restrictions. We are deeply concerned by Iran's steps to reduce compliance with the deal. We are working closely with remaining JCPoA parties to address this and we urge Iran to reverse the steps it has taken.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-10-30T16:39:59.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151998/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151998/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151998/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-23","Iran: Nuclear Fuels","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government in which areas Iran has breached the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action; and why Her Majesty's Government have not withdrawn from that Plan.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151999","Cabinet Office","false","2019-11-04","<p>The Government deplores the inexcusable intimidation and abuse of ministers and MPs in public life; nobody should have to suffer abuse and intimidation simply for doing their job.</p><p>It is a wide-ranging and complex issue to tackle - it cannot be achieved through one action alone and the Government is working with the police, political parties, Parliament’s security teams, the Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority (IPSA), the electoral community, civil society groups and other organisations.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2019-11-04T12:18:36.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151999/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151999/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151999/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-10-23","Ministers: Harassment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they will take to protect ministers from abuse and intimidation when leaving the Parliamentary Estate.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152000","The Senior Deputy Speaker","false","2019-10-30","<p>The Parliamentary Security Department (PSD) works closely with the Metropolitan Police (MPS). PSD officials meet with the MPS frequently to discuss anticipated or ongoing issues, which can include intimidation of Parliamentarians and staff by protestors when entering and leaving the estate.</p><p>PSD holds a weekly meeting with the MPS, Black Rod and the Serjeant at Arms to assess forthcoming events for potential issues around access and security, enabling PSD and MPS responses to be updated accordingly. For security reasons we do not provide details of security arrangements.</p><p>When high levels of protest activity are expected, Parliamentarians are sent communications advising them of access information and security advice. Parliamentarians are also encouraged to raise any security concerns with the Director of Security for Parliament, and to raise access queries with Black Rod.</p>",,"Lord McFall of Alcluith",,"2019-10-30T12:36:57.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152000/answer","Biography information for Lord McFall of Alcluith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152000/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152000/answer",,,,,"204",,"Senior Deputy Speaker (HoL)","2019-10-23","Peers: Harassment","2","House of Lords","To ask the Senior Deputy Speaker what representations, if any, the House of Lords Administration has made to the Metropolitan Police regarding protestors intimidating Parliamentarians leaving the Parliamentary Estate.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152001","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>Enforcement of road traffic law is an operational matter for individual Chief Officers of police in conjunction with local policing plans. We will continue to support the police to ensure they have the tools needed to enforce road traffic legisaltion including those relating to electric scooters.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2019-11-05T17:43:05.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152001/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152001/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152001/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-23","Electric Scooters: Road Traffic Offences","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions they intend to have with the police to enforce the prohibition against two-wheeled battery-operated scooters using pavements and highways.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152002","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-31","<p>Local authorities already have powers to deal with hire bicycles if they are causing an obstruction or nuisance, and are also able to introduce local byelaws as appropriate. The Government therefore has no immediate plans to introduce any new legislation, but will continue to monitor the impacts of bike hire schemes and to work with local authorities and scheme operators as appropriate on ways of addressing any problems that arise.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Vere of Norbiton",,"2019-10-31T15:31:50.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152002/answer","Biography information for Baroness Vere of Norbiton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152002/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152002/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-23","Bicycles: Hire Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to consult on changing the law around the ability of members of the public, councils and any other organisations (1) to remove, (2) to take, (3) to destroy, or (4) to otherwise dispose of, undocked bikes for hire which have been left on pavements.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152003","Department for Education","false","2019-10-31","<p>Racial harassment is unacceptable and we cannot tolerate staff and students being victims of it at our world-leading universities.</p><p> </p><p>Higher education providers have clear responsibilities under the Equality Act 2010 and should discharge their responsibilities fully and have robust policies and procedures in place to comply with the law, to investigate and swiftly address incidents reported to them.</p><p> </p><p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) inquiry has made an important contribution to our knowledge of the extent of racism in higher education. The government will look closely at EHRC’s recommendations. Although some progress has been made, it is clear there is still more to do. Universities have clear responsibilities in this regard and I expect them to take these seriously.</p>",,"Baroness Berridge",,"2019-10-31T13:45:16.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152003/answer","Biography information for Baroness Berridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152003/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152003/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-23","Universities: Racial Harassment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what proposals they will make in response to the report of the Equality and Human Rights Commission Tackling Racial Harassment: Universities Challenged, published on 23 October.","false","Biography information for Lord Boateng",,"Lord Boateng","HL347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152004","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-11-05","<p>Gym clothing is available for women who request it in all prisons in England. A new range of gym kit has recently been approved following consultation with managers and women in the public sector estate.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2019-11-05T13:04:07.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152004/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152004/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152004/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-23","Prisoners: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether gym clothing is available to all women prisoners who request it in every prison in England.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradley",,"Lord Bradley","HL348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152005","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-31","<p>On 30 September, the Government announced a package of funding and policy measures to support buses, set out in <em>A Better Deal for Bus Users</em>. This includes £220 million of new funding for buses, in addition to the £250 million paid every year in Bus Service Operators Grant.</p><p> </p><p><em>A Better Deal for Bus Users</em> contains a commitment to review this Grant to ensure it supports the environment and improved passenger journeys.</p><p> </p><p>It also included a commitment to produce a National Bus Strategy for England, accompanied by a long-term funding settlement to be agreed at the next Spending Review, expected to be in Summer 2020.</p>",,"Baroness Vere of Norbiton",,"2019-10-31T15:32:11.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152005/answer","Biography information for Baroness Vere of Norbiton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152005/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152005/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-23","Bus Service Operators Grant","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the review of Bus Service Operators Grant announced by the Chancellor of the Exchequer will include the allocation of new money for the bus industry.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152006","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-31","<p>All of these projects are within the £220 million announced by the Government on 30 September, and comprise additional funding on top of the £250m that the Government already spends every year supporting bus services.</p>",,"Baroness Vere of Norbiton",,"2019-10-31T15:32:58.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152006/answer","Biography information for Baroness Vere of Norbiton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152006/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1152006/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-23","Bus Services: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether their following commitments amount to new money allocated to buses: (1) £20 million for bus priority measures in the West Midlands, (2) up to £50 million to deliver Britain's first all-electric bus town or city, (3) £30 million to local government to improve services or restore services which have been lost, and (4) £20 million to support demand-responsive services.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL350"
