"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151362","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-10-29","<p>We have been working with stakeholders to consider this risk and implement the measures needed to mitigate it, including reforming and simplifying the process for registering rights of way. The legislation will contain an exception for rights of way in current use in order to avoid losing valuable paths that are still active.</p>","Taunton Deane","Rebecca Pow",,"2019-10-29T12:40:38.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151362/answer","Biography information for Rebecca Pow","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151362/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151362/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-22","Rights of Way","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment the Government has made of the risk of ancient rights of way being lost due to them not being registered by local authorities before the 2026 deadline.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","3635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151363","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-10-29","<p>We recognise the need for sufficient time to register public rights of way before the cut-off date. Stakeholder views on whether there is a need to extend the deadline are mixed, and will be taken into account, although no decision has yet been taken. We will continue to consider views and weigh up the need to extend the deadline against the certainty that the cut-off date will bring.</p>","Taunton Deane","Rebecca Pow",,"2019-10-29T12:33:42.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151363/answer","Biography information for Rebecca Pow","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151363/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151363/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-22","Rights of Way","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the potential merits of extending the deadline for registering public rights of way beyond 2026.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","3636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151364","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-29","<p>The Department currently has no plans to consult on increasing the eligibility for bereavement support payment to include cohabitees.</p><p> </p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-10-29T14:24:12.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151364/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151364/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151364/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-22","Bereavement Support Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans her Department has to consult on increasing the eligibility for bereavement support payment to include cohabitees.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","3788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151365","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-29","<p>We intend to carry out an evaluation of Bereavement Support Payment once sufficient evidence is available for this comparatively new benefit, to enable us to evaluate the policy.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-10-29T14:23:57.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151365/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151365/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151365/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-22","Bereavement Support Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment her Department has made of the adequacy of the (a) 18-month limit for receiving bereavement support payment and (b) three-month limit for claiming bereavement support payment.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","3789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151366","Attorney General","false","2019-10-30","<p>The Jain and Zoroastrian communities of this country have made, and continue to make a positive contribution to life in the United Kingdom. The Government values this contribution enormously.</p><p> </p><p>The Attorney General’s Office (AGO) has not organised any national events in the last two years where it has invited representatives of the Jain or Zoroastrian communities. The AGO is a small and specialised Ministerial Department that does not commonly organise national events. The AGO will endeavour to invite representatives of the Jain and Zoroastrian communities to relevant events.</p><p> </p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2019-10-30T16:28:45.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151366/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151366/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151366/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2019-10-22","Attorney General: Jainism and Zoroastrianism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, when representatives of the (a) Jain and (b) Zoroastrian community were invited to national events organised by his Department in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","3523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151367","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-30","<p>The NHS Long Term Plan published on 7 January 2019, set out a 10-year strategy for the National Health Service. It sets out how the NHS will spend the £33.9 billion cash terms annual increase going into the NHS budget by 2023/24.</p><p>It is for NHS England and NHS Improvement to make decisions about how to prioritise the how they meet the Long Term Plans commitments on dentistry from within the total settlement.</p><p>Over the NHS Long Term Plan period, to 2023/24, NHS England and NHS Improvement’s commissioning allocations for dental services are planned to increase to cover population growth, increasing demand for services and inflationary cost pressures.</p><p>NHS England and NHS Improvement are working closely with the Department to introduce a new NHS dental contract that will focus on achieving good oral health and increasing access to NHS dentistry, with a particular focus on improving the oral health of children, which are all key deliverables of the Long Term Plan.</p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","3638","2019-10-30T17:46:47.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151367/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151367/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151367/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-22","Dental Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what share of new funding under the NHS Long Term Plan is being assigned to increasing the capacity of NHS dental services.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","3637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151368","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-30","<p>When a Universal Credit (UC) claimant suffers a bereavement there are easements to work-related requirement which can be applied. These will be discussed and agreed, on an individual basis, with the claimant’s Work Coach or Case Manager. In some circumstances payment of UC, that would otherwise reduce or stop following a bereavement, can continue for a short time. This is called a ‘Bereavement run-on’, and may be applied when a partner or dependent child dies.</p><p> </p><p>The ‘Bereavement run-on’ results in UC continuing to be paid as if there had been no change of circumstances for the assessment period in which the death occurs and the following two assessment periods.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-10-30T17:03:08.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151368/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151368/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151368/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-22","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of the six-month limit on the easement of work-related requirements for universal credit for bereavement of a partner or child.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","3790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151369","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-10-28","<p>Ministers have attended a number of key events coordinated by Jain and Zoroastrian organisations, and officials have invited representatives from both communities to participate in roundtable discussions where relevant issues are discussed.</p><p> </p><p>The Jain and Zoroastrian communities of this country have made, and continue to make a positive contribution to life in the United Kingdom. The Government values this contribution enormously.</p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","2657","2019-10-28T16:52:34.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151369/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151369/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151369/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-10-22","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Jainism and Zoroastrianism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, when representatives of the (a) Jain and (b) Zoroastrian community were invited to national events organised by her Department in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","3524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151370","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-30","<p>The NHS Long Term Plan published on 7 January 2019, set out a 10-year strategy for the National Health Service. It sets out how the NHS will spend the £33.9 billion cash terms annual increase going into the NHS budget by 2023/24.</p><p>It is for NHS England and NHS Improvement to make decisions about how to prioritise the how they meet the Long Term Plans commitments on dentistry from within the total settlement.</p><p>Over the NHS Long Term Plan period, to 2023/24, NHS England and NHS Improvement’s commissioning allocations for dental services are planned to increase to cover population growth, increasing demand for services and inflationary cost pressures.</p><p>NHS England and NHS Improvement are working closely with the Department to introduce a new NHS dental contract that will focus on achieving good oral health and increasing access to NHS dentistry, with a particular focus on improving the oral health of children, which are all key deliverables of the Long Term Plan.</p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","3637","2019-10-30T17:46:47.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151370/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151370/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151370/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-22","Dental Services: North Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what proportion of new funding under the NHS Long Term Plan he plans to allocate to NHS dental services in the Vale of York.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","3638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151371","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-10-30","<p>Ministers have attended a number of key events coordinated by Jain and Zoroastrian organisations, and officials have invited representatives from both communities to participate in roundtable discussions where relevant issues are discussed.</p><p>The Jain and Zoroastrian communities of this country have made and continue to make a positive contribution to life in the UK. The Government values this contribution enormously.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2019-10-30T17:40:44.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151371/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151371/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151371/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-22","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Jainism and Zoroastrianism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when representatives of the (a) Jain and (b) Zoroastrian community were invited to national events organised by his Department in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","3525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151372","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-30","<p>The Government has no plans to reopen the pleural plaques compensation scheme, which operated between 2 August 2010 and 1 August 2011.</p><p> </p><p>The scheme operated as an extra-statutory one, making £5000 payments on an ex-gratia basis to applicants who fulfilled the scheme’s criteria, namely that they were individuals who had begun, but not resolved, a legal claim for compensation for pleural plaques at the time of the House of Lords ruling in October 2007 in the case of Rothwell v Chemical &amp; Insulating Co Ltd [2007] UKHL 39. That ruling had held that the occurrence of pleural plaques is not a compensatable disease.</p><p> </p><p>Eligibility for the scheme was limited to that category of people as they would have had an understandable expectation of receiving compensation when they began their claim, an expectation which would not have been shared by those diagnosed later.</p>","Aldridge-Brownhills","Wendy Morton",,"2019-10-30T17:54:39.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151372/answer","Biography information for Wendy Morton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151372/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151372/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-22","Pleural Plaques: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans he has to re-establish the right to compensation for people in England and Wales who developed pleural plaques as a result of exposure to asbestos.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","3639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151373","Department for Education","false","2019-10-28","<p>The information requested is not held centrally as each event is handled on a case by case basis.</p><p>The government is committed to working with all communities and ensuring that the full breadth and diversity is represented. The Jain and Zoroastrian communities of this country have made and continue to make a positive contribution to life in the United Kingdom. The government values this contribution enormously.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2019-10-28T14:09:45.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151373/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151373/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151373/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-22","Department for Education: Jainism and Zoroastrianism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when representatives of the (a) Jain and (b) Zoroastrian community were invited to national events organised by his Department in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","3526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151374","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-10-28","<p>Government Ministers have attended a number of key events coordinated by Jain and Zoroastrian organisations, and officials from MHCLG have invited representatives from both communities to participate in roundtable discussions where relevant issues are discussed.</p><p>The Jain and Zoroastrian communities of this country have made, and continue to make a positive contribution to life in the United Kingdom. The Government values this contribution enormously.</p><p> </p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2019-10-28T16:09:15.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151374/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151374/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151374/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-10-22","Department for Exiting the European Union: Jainism and Zoroastrianism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, when representatives of the (a) Jain and (b) Zoroastrian community were invited to national events organised by his Department in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","3527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151375","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-10-28","<p>We are aware of concerns about the potential for excessive spending in games, particularly by young people. These concerns, and particularly those regarding the availability of loot boxes, are discussed in the recent DCMS Select Committee report on Immersive and Addictive Technologies. We are currently considering the Report and its recommendations and will respond in due course.</p><p> </p><p>We do not currently have an estimate of the amount spent by people under 18 on in-app or in-game purchases over the last 5 years. However, we note that the Gambling Commission’s new research on Children and Young People found that of the 11-16 year olds taking part in their survey, 52% had heard of the availability of in-game items and of these 44% had paid money to open loot boxes.</p><p> </p><p>We encourage parents concerned about in-game spending by their children to consider using the parental controls available on devices to disable this function.</p><p><br></p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","3533","2019-10-28T16:37:08.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151375/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151375/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151375/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-10-22","Gambling: Video Games","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to prevent young people spending excessively on loot boxes in computer games.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","3532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151376","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-28","<p>Non-molestation orders are made by the court to protect individuals from the harm of domestic violence. They can, where necessary, extend to protect children.</p><p>Non-molestation applications are either made ‘without notice’ to the respondent, usually if the applicant is seeking immediate protection, or ‘on notice’ to the respondent. The number of non-molestation orders made in each of the last 9 calendar years is shown in table 1 below. The data covers England and Wales.</p><p><strong>Table 1: Non-molestation orders made in England and Wales</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>21,194</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>19,556</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>19,403</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>22,284</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>23,999</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>23,630</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>23,647</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>25,750</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018</p></td><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>27,183</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Source:<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/family-court-statistics-quarterly-april-to-june-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/family-court-statistics-quarterly-april-to-june-2019</a></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>We do not hold data on how many people have represented themselves when applying for an order.</p><p>Her Majesty’s Court and Tribunals Service publish a range of guidance on Gov.Uk including eligibility for obtaining orders, how to apply for an injunction if you've been the victim of domestic violence, how to apply for a non-molestation order and an occupation order and how to serve applications. Links to the guidance are below:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/injunction-domestic-violence/eligibility-non-molestation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/injunction-domestic-violence/eligibility-non-molestation</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/form-fl401-application-for-a-non-molestation-order-occupation-order" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/form-fl401-application-for-a-non-molestation-order-occupation-order</a></p>","Aldridge-Brownhills","Wendy Morton","3642 ; 3643","2019-10-28T17:34:24.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151376/answer","Biography information for Wendy Morton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151376/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151376/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-22","Non-molestation Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many non-molestation orders have been issued in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","3640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1151377","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-28","<table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>VOLUME OF REFUSALS</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>% OF APPLICATIONS REFUSED</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>YEAR</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FEMALES (a)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>TOTAL (b)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FEMALES (a)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>TOTAL (b)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>29</p></td><td><p>35</p></td><td><p>0.25%</p></td><td><p>0.30%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>0.11%</p></td><td><p>0.13%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>19</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>0.17%</p></td><td><p>0.22%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>67</p></td><td><p>68</p></td><td><p>0.44%</p></td><td><p>0.45%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>123</p></td><td><p>131</p></td><td><p>0.87%</p></td><td><p>0.93%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-2016</p></td><td><p>127</p></td><td><p>132</p></td><td><p>0.94%</p></td><td><p>0.98%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-2017</p></td><td><p>222</p></td><td><p>235</p></td><td><p>1.67%</p></td><td><p>1.77%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-2018</p></td><td><p>282</p></td><td><p>307</p></td><td><p>2.10%</p></td><td><p>2.29%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018-2019</p></td><td><p>380</p></td><td><p>406</p></td><td><p>2.87%</p></td><td><p>3.07%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Figures are based on the volume of applications made rather than the number of discrete individuals. One person may make more than one application for legal aid.</p><p> </p><p>Applications for legal aid when requesting a non-molestation orders will only be rejected when a court is unlikely to grant an order, for instance where other help and support is already in place.</p>","Aldridge-Brownhills","Wendy Morton",,"2019-10-28T17:20:00.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/res